Sparkify Project Workspace¶

This workspace contains a tiny subset (128MB) of the full dataset available (12GB). Feel free to use this workspace to build your project, or to explore a smaller subset with Spark before deploying your cluster on the cloud. Instructions for setting up your Spark cluster is included in the last lesson of the Extracurricular Spark Course content.

You can follow the steps below to guide your data analysis and model building portion of this project.

Project Overview¶

The app contains data of a fictional music streaming service similar to Spotify. Goal is to predict which user is likely to churn. In order to keep the customers, discounts or special offers can be sent to the specific user.

def clean_data(data):
    '''
    Input: Dataset
    Output: Cleaned dataset
    '''
    # Remove duplicates in userId
    data.select("userId").dropDuplicates().count()
    # Remove strings and empty values
    data_clean = data.dropna(how = 'any', subset = ['userId', 'sessionId'])
    data_clean = data_clean.filter(data_clean['userId'] != '')
    return data_clean

Convert time-related features¶

In [11]:
def convert(data):
    '''
    Input: Dataset
    Output: Dataset with converted registration date and hour 
    '''
    # Convert registration date
    get_date = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).strftime("%Y-%m-%d"))
    data = data.withColumn("registration_date", get_date(data.registration))
    # Convert hour
    get_hour = udf(lambda x: datetime.datetime.fromtimestamp(x / 1000.0).strftime("%H"))
    data = data.withColumn("hour", get_hour(data.ts))
    
    return data

Define Churn¶

Once you've done some preliminary analysis, create a column Churn to use as the label for your model. I suggest using the Cancellation Confirmation events to define your churn, which happen for both paid and free users. As a bonus task, you can also look into the Downgrade events.

Churn defined by userId and Cancellation Confirmation¶

In [15]:
def churn(data):
    '''
    Input: Dataset
    Output: Dataset of churned and non churned users
    '''
    data.createOrReplaceTempView('user_log_table')

    # data with churned users
    churned_users = spark.sql('SELECT DISTINCT userId, 1 as churn FROM user_log_table WHERE Page = "Cancellation Confirmation"')
    # data with non churned users
    non_churned_users = spark.sql('SELECT DISTINCT userId, 0 as churn FROM user_log_table \
                      WHERE userId NOT IN (SELECT DISTINCT userId FROM user_log_table WHERE Page = "Cancellation Confirmation")')

    # Creating a combined dataset of churned users and non churned users
    combined_churn = churned_users.union(non_churned_users)
    combined_churn.createOrReplaceTempView('churn_and_non_churn')
    combined_churn = spark.sql('SELECT * FROM churn_and_non_churn')

    return combined_churn

Feature Engineering¶

Once you've familiarized yourself with the data, build out the features you find promising to train your model on. To work with the full dataset, you can follow the following steps.

  • Write a script to extract the necessary features from the smaller subset of data
  • Ensure that your script is scalable, using the best practices discussed in Lesson 3
  • Try your script on the full data set, debugging your script if necessary

If you are working in the classroom workspace, you can just extract features based on the small subset of data contained here. Be sure to transfer over this work to the larger dataset when you work on your Spark cluster.

Following features has been used:¶

1. Gender¶

2. Thumps up¶

3. Thumps down¶

4. Listening time(length)¶

5. Number of songs per user(song)¶

6. Free or paid user(level)¶

In [25]:
def features(data=churn_data):
    '''
    Input: Dataset
    Output: Dataset with features(Gender, Thumps up, Thumps down, Listening time,
                                  Number of songs per user, free or paid user) Changed churned to label and int.      
    '''
    # Gender
    gender_num = churn_data\
           .select('userId','gender')\
           .dropDuplicates() \
           .replace(['M','F'],['0','1'],'gender')\
           .select('userId',col('gender').cast('int'))\
           .withColumnRenamed('gender', 'gender_num') 
    
    # Thumbs up
    thumbs_up = churn_data \
             .select('userID','page') \
             .where(churn_data.page == 'Thumbs Up') \
             .groupBy('userID') \
             .count() \
             .withColumnRenamed('count', 'thumbs_up') 
    
    # Thumps down
    thumbs_down = churn_data \
                 .select('userID','page') \
                 .where(churn_data.page == 'Thumbs Down') \
                 .groupBy('userID') \
                 .count() \
                 .withColumnRenamed('count', 'thumbs_down')
    
    # Listening Time
    listening_time = churn_data \
            .select('userId','length') \
            .groupby(['userId']) \
            .sum() \
            .withColumnRenamed('sum(length)','listening_time')

    # Number of songs per user
    song_per_user = churn_data \
                  .select("userId","song")\
                  .groupby("userId")\
                  .count()\
                  .withColumnRenamed("count","song_per_user")
    
    # Free or paid user to int
    level_num = churn_data \
         .select('userId','level')\
         .replace(['free','paid'],['0','1'],'level')\
         .select('userId',col('level').cast('int'))\
         .withColumnRenamed('level', 'level_num') 
    
    # Change churn to label
    label = churn_data \
        .select('userId', col('churn').alias('label')) \
        .dropDuplicates()

    # Join dataset
    feature_data = song_per_user.join(gender_num,'userID','outer') \
              .join(thumbs_up,'userID','outer') \
              .join(thumbs_down, 'userID','outer') \
              .join(listening_time,'userID','outer') \
              .join(level_num,'userID','outer') \
              .join(label,'userID','outer') \
              .drop('userID') \
              .fillna(0)


    
    return feature_data

Transform and scale features¶

In [28]:
def transform_scale(feature_data):
    '''
    Input: Features
    Output: Transformed and scaled features
    '''
    # Transform features
    cols = ['song_per_user', 'gender_num', 'thumbs_up', 'thumbs_down','level_num','listening_time']
    assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=cols, outputCol="NumFeatures")
    data = assembler.transform(feature_data)
    
    # Scale features
    scaler = StandardScaler(inputCol="NumFeatures", outputCol="features", withStd=True)
    scalerModel = scaler.fit(data)
    data = scalerModel.transform(data)
    
    return data

def ml_model_train_validate(model):
    start_time = time.time()

    f_score = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(metricName='f1')
    
    model_train = model.fit(train)
    model_test = model_train.transform(validation)

    evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(predictionCol='prediction')
    
    print("Model is:", model)
    print("Accuracy:")
    print(evaluator.evaluate(model_test,{evaluator.metricName: 'accuracy'}))
    print("F-1 score:")
    print(evaluator.evaluate(model_test, {evaluator.metricName: 'f1'}))
    print("%s seconds \n" % (time.time() - start_time))
    print("----------------------------------------\n")
    return model

Results¶

It's obvious that Gradient Boosted Tree overfitted, due the highly imbalanced(much more non_churned user than churned user in dataset)dataset. With respect to training time, I would choose Random Forest Clasifier.

Future Improvements¶

  1. Training the model on the big dataset would help a lot.
  2. Extract and use more features, that would lead to a more robust model.
  3. Tune Hyperparameters
  4. Random over- or down-sampling could be applied in order to get a more balanced dataset.
